    <section>
        <h>dependents</h>
        <section id="subject">
            <h>subject</h>
            <p>The subject of <g>stad</g> is generally a noun expression denoting a human (or other animal) – <ul>
                    <li><m>Stad mi.</m>
                        <en>I stopped.</en></li>
                    <li><m>Stad!</m>
                        <en>Stop!</en></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>Some examples – <ul id="deps-sbj-hum-xs">
                    <li>older pedagogical examples – <xl id="deps-sbj-hum-older-pedag">
                            <li>
                                <gd>Bha an latha brèagha blàth is thug an athair leis Iain agus Anna
                                    anns a’ chàr. Chaidh iad sìos taobh an locha is <m>stad iad</m>
                                    aig àite bòidheach gorm. [...]</gd>
                                <tr>The day was lovely and warm and their father took John and Ann
                                    in the car. They went down the side of the lake and they stopped
                                    at a beautiful green place. [...]</tr>
                                <ref text="621">td. 6</ref>
                            </li>
                        </xl>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </section>
        <section id="comps">
            <h>complements</h>
            <section id="deps-comp-none">
                <h>strict intransitive</h>
                <p><g>stad</g> can occur without any complements, as a strict intransitive verb – <ul>
                        <li><m>Stad sinn.</m>
                            <en>We stopped.</en></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>Some examples – <ul id="deps-comps-none-xs">
                        <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="deps-comps-none-pedag">
                                <li>
                                    <gd>Stad iad aig bun na beinne.</gd>
                                    <tr>They halted at the foot of the mountain.</tr>
                                    <ref text="605">td. 353</ref>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <gd>Stad e gu h-obann.</gd>
                                    <tr>He stopped suddenly.</tr>
                                    <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                                </li>
                            </xl></li>
                        <li>older pedagogical examples – <xl id="deps-comps-none-older-pedag">
                                <li>
                                    <gd>Bha an latha brèagha blàth is thug an athair leis Iain agus
                                        Anna anns a’ chàr. Chaidh iad sìos taobh an locha is <m>stad
                                            iad</m> aig àite bòidheach gorm. [...]</gd>
                                    <tr>The day was lovely and warm and the father took John and Ann
                                        in the car. They went down the side of the lake and they
                                        stopped at a beautiful green place. [...]</tr>
                                    <ref text="621">td. 6</ref>
                                </li>
                            </xl></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </section>
            <section id="deps-comps-trans">
                <h>transitive</h>
                <p><g>stad</g> can occur (at least in very recent usage) with a noun expression as complement, as a transitive verb
                    – <ul>
                        <li><m>Stad mi an càr.</m>
                            <en>I stopped the car.</en></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>Some examples – <ul id="deps-comps-trans-xs">
                        <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="deps-comps-trans-pedag">
                                <li>
                                    <gd>Stad e an làraidh.</gd>
                                    <tr>He stopped the lorry.</tr>
                                    <ref text="605">td. 353</ref>
                                </li>
                            </xl></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </section>
            <section>
                <h>prepositions</h>
                <module id="deps-comps-dhe" status="bronze">
                    <h>stad de [a] ...</h>
                    <p><g>stad</g> can take a (verbal noun) complement introduced by the partitive
                        preposition <a href="?gd=de"><g>de [a]</g></a>
                        <en>of</en> – <ul>
                            <li><m>Stad i a dh’ithe nan ùbhlan.</m>
                                <en>She stopped eating the apples.</en></li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                    <p>Some examples – <ul id="deps-comps-dhe-xs">
                            <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="deps-comps-dhe-pedag">
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>Stad iad a dh’iomradh le chèile.</gd>
                                        <tr>They both stopped rowing.</tr>
                                        <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>Bha i air stad a chur.</gd>
                                        <tr>It had stopped snowing.</tr>
                                        <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>Stad i den ghàireachdaich.</gd>
                                        <tr>She stopped laughing.</tr>
                                        <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                                        <note>definite article here</note>
                                    </li>
                                </xl></li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </module>
                <module status="bronze" id="deps-comps-le">
                    <h>stad le ...</h>
                    <p><g>na stad <a href="?gd=le">le</a> bhith a’ dèanamh rud</g>
                        <en>not stop at doing something, go beyond doing something</en></p>
                    <p>Pedagogical examples – <xl id="deps-comps-le-pedag">
                            <li>
                                <gd>Ach cha do stad iad idir le bhith ag iomradh air dreasa a’
                                    bhoireannaich.</gd>
                                <tr>But in no way did they stop at remarking on the woman’s
                                    clothes.</tr>
                                <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                            </li>
                        </xl>
                    </p>
                </module>
            </section>
            <section id="deps-comps-other">
                <h>other</h>
                <p>Pedagogical examples – <xl id="deps-comps-other-pedag">
                        <li>
                            <gd>Ach stad ort!</gd>
                            <tr>But stop!</tr>
                            <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                            <note>impersonal? reflexive? Mandic: Could this be a v. noun in an elliptical expression? 
                                Cf. ‘cuir stad air’...</note>
                        </li>
                    </xl>
                </p>
            </section>
        </section>
        <section id="deps-mods">
            <h>modifiers</h>
            <p><g>stad</g> can appear with the following modifiers – <ul>
                    <li>locative – <ul>
                            <li><g>stad <a href="?gd=aig">aig</a> ...</g>
                                <en>stop at</en> – <ul>
                                    <li>older pedagogical examples – <xl
                                            id="deps-mods-aig-older-pedag">
                                            <li>
                                                <gd>Bha an latha brèagha blàth is thug an athair
                                                  leis Iain agus Anna anns a’ chàr. Chaidh iad sìos
                                                  taobh an locha is <m>stad iad aig àite bòidheach
                                                  gorm</m>. [...]</gd>
                                                <tr>The day was lovely and warm and their father
                                                  took John and Ann in the car. They went down the
                                                  side of the lake and they stopped at a beautiful
                                                  green place. [...]</tr>
                                                <ref text="621">td. 6</ref>
                                            </li>
                                        </xl>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>purposive – <ul>
                            <li><g>stad <a href="?gd=do^preposition">do</a> [a] ...</g>
                                <en>stop to (do)</en> – <ul>
                                    <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="deps-mods-dha-pedag">
                                            <li>
                                                <gd>Feumaidh sinn stad a dh’ithe a
                                                  dh’aithghearr.</gd>
                                                <tr>We must stop to eat soon.</tr>
                                                <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                                            </li>
                                        </xl></li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <section id="deps-mods-compounds">
                <h>compounds</h>
                <p>Some compounds – <ul>
                        <li><g>stad beag</g>
                            <en>a pause</en></li>
                        <li><g>stad bus</g>
                            <en>bus stop</en></li>
                        <li><g>stad cofaidh</g>
                            <en>coffee break</en>
                            <xl id="cofaidh">
                                <li>
                                    <gd>rè nan stadan-cofaidh</gd>
                                    <tr>during the coffee breaks</tr>
                                    <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                                </li>
                            </xl>
                        </li>
                        <li><g>stad losgaidh</g>
                            <en>ceasefire</en></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </section>

        </section>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h>uses</h>
        <section>
            <h>derivatives</h>
            <module id="stad-noun" status="bronze">
                <h>stad <masc/></h>
                <p><g>stad</g>
                    <en>stop, halt, pause, end, cessation</en> is a (at least synchronically) deverbal masculine noun, derived
                    from the verb <g>stad</g>, with genitive singular form <g>stada</g> and plural
                        <g>stadan</g>.</p>
                <section>
                    <h>uses</h>
                    <section>
                        <h>object</h>
                        <module id="uses-derivs-stad-uses-obj-dean" status="bronze">
                            <h>dèan stad</h>
                            <p><g><a href="?gd=dèan">dèan</a> stad</g>
                                <en>make a stop, stop</en></p>
                            <p>Pedagogical examples – <xl id="dean_stad-pedag">
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>Nì sinn stad an seo.</gd>
                                        <tr>We’ll stop/wait here.</tr>
                                        <ref text="605">td. 353</ref>
                                    </li>
                                </xl>
                            </p>
                        </module>
                        <module id="uses-derivs-stad-uses-obj-cuir" status="bronze">
                            <h>cuir stad air ...</h>
                            <p><g><a href="?gd=cuir">cuir</a> stad air ...</g>
                                <en>put a stop to, stop</en></p>
                            <p>Pedagogical examples – <xl id="cuir_stad-pedag">
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>Cuiridh mi stad air do shràidearachd!</gd>
                                        <tr>I’ll put a stop to your stravaigin!</tr>
                                        <ref text="605">td. 353</ref>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>cuir stad air</gd>
                                        <tr>inhibit, stop</tr>
                                        <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                                    </li>
                                </xl>
                            </p>
                        </module>
                    </section>
                    <section>
                        <h>complement</h>
                        <module id="uses-derivs-stad-uses-comp-ag" status="bronze">
                            <h>a’ stad</h>
                            <p><g><a href="?gd=ag">a’</a> stad</g>
                                <en>in the process of stopping</en></p>
                            <p>Pedagogical examples – <xl id="prog-pedag">
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>Tha an trèana a’ stad ann an ...</gd>
                                        <tr>The trains calls at ...</tr>
                                        <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                                        <note>habitual</note>
                                    </li>
                                </xl>
                            </p>
                        </module>
                        <module id="uses-derivs-stad-uses-comp-an" status="bronze">
                            <h>na* stad</h>
                            <p><g><a href="?gd=an^preposition">na*</a> stad</g>
                                <en>in a state of having stopped</en>, cf. <a
                                    href="?q=verbal_aspect">retrospective</a> aspect.</p>
                            <p>Pedagogical examples – <xl id="uses-derivs-stad-uses-comp-an-pedag">
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>Bha am bus na stad.</gd>
                                        <tr>The bus was stationary.</tr>
                                        <ref text="605">td. 353</ref>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>Tha a’ chùis na stad.</gd>
                                        <tr>The affair/matter/business is at a standstill.</tr>
                                        <ref text="605">td. 353</ref>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>Bha a’ chùis a-nis na stad.</gd>
                                        <tr>The matter was now in abeyance.</tr>
                                        <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                                    </li>
                                </xl>
                            </p>
                        </module>
                        <module status="bronze" id="uses-derivs-stad-uses-comp-gu">
                            <h>gu stad</h>
                            <p><g><a href="?gd=gu^preposition">gu</a> stad</g>
                                <en>to a stop</en>.</p>
                            <section>
                                <h>uses</h>
                                <section>
                                    <h>complement</h>
                                    <module id="uses-derivs-stad-uses-comp-thig-gu" status="bronze">
                                        <h>thig gu stad</h>
                                        <p><g><a href="?gd=thig">thig</a> gu stad</g>
                                            <en>come to a halt, stop</en></p>
                                        <p>Pedagogical examples – <xl
                                                id="uses-derivs-stad-uses-comp-thig-gu-pedag">
                                                <li>
                                                  <gd>Thàinig i gu stad.</gd>
                                                  <tr>She came to a halt/stop.</tr>
                                                  <ref text="605">td. 353</ref>
                                                </li>
                                                <li>
                                                  <gd>thig gu stad</gd>
                                                  <tr>land</tr>
                                                  <ref text="601">td. 548</ref>
                                                </li>
                                            </xl>
                                        </p>
                                    </module>
                                    <module id="uses-derivs-stad-uses-comp-thoir-gu" status="bronze">
                                        <h>thoir ... gu stad</h>
                                        <p><g><a href="?gd=thoir">thoir</a> ... gu stad</g>
